For this, we need to show that if $I$ is matchable (i.e., there exists a matching $M$ such that $I \subseteq V(G, M)$), and $J \subseteq I$, then $J$ is also matchable.

The proof is straightforward: if $M$ is a matching such that $I \subseteq V(G, M)$, then clearly $J \subseteq I \subseteq V(G, M)$, so $J$ is also matchable with the same matching $M$.

