    -- The components of G' = (V(G), M_I Δ M_J) are alternating paths and cycles
    -- The endpoints of J \ I and I \ J are endpoints of alternating paths
    -- Since |I| < |J|, we have |I \ J| < |J \ I|
    -- There exists some v ∈ J \ I in an alternating path where the other endpoint is not in I \ J
    -- If the other endpoint is matched by M_J, then the path is augmenting
    -- We can form a new matching M_I' = M_I Δ P
    -- This new matching matches all of I and also v ∈ J. So I ∪ {v} is matchable.
```

